    "created_at": "2021-05-06T09:47:24Z",
    "updated_at": "2021-05-06T09:47:24Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Yes I think that's intentional. `EncodePoint` encodes the coordinates while `ToBytes` encodes the point after affine transformation.\r\n`EncodePoint` encodes [x1, x0, y1, y0].\r\n`ToBytes()` encodes [p0[1], p0[0], p1[1], p0[0]] with p being in the affine representation, p0, p1 of type `Fe2`.\r\nFrom the documentation for type `Fe2`:\r\n```\r\n// fe2 is element representation of 'fp2' which is quadratic extension of base field 'fp'\r\n// Representation follows c[0] + c[1] * u encoding order.\r\n```\r\nSo c[1] represents the upper bytes of the `fe2` element and c[0] the lower bytes",
